 has historically been privileged by cinema and has led to the current climate crisis. While some chapters question the very nature of this enterprise—whether cinema should or even could actualize such a maneuver beyond the human—others signal the ways in which the category of the "human" itself is interrogated by Latin American cinema, revealed to be a fiction that excludes more than it unifies. This volume explores how the moving image reinforces or contests the division between human and nonhuman, and troubles the settler epistemic partition of culture and nature that is at the core of the climate crisis. As the first volume to specifically address how such questions are staged by Latin American cinema, this book brings together analysis of films that respond to environmental degradation, as well as those that articulate a posthumanist ethos that blurs the line between species.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aClimatic changes in motion pictures. 0aEcology in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszLatin AmericaxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictureszLatin AmericaxHistory. 0aMotion pictures--Latin America--History and criticism. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArce, Tomás Emilio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackmore, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBundy, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDara